{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0d96e7b0-44e0-11ed-8948-1e83899eddd5","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"ref":"99ee59e6-45c2-11ed-9816-b5a46be8e501","type":"stage-layout-root","sections":[{"ref":"99ee59e2-45c2-11ed-9816-b5a46be8e501","type":"stage-section","rows":[{"ref":"99ee59e1-45c2-11ed-9816-b5a46be8e501","type":"stage-layout-row","columns":[{"ref":"99ee59e0-45c2-11ed-9816-b5a46be8e501","type":"stage-layout-column","stageElements":[{"ref":"afceb7ec-1a6f-4309-a553-f54b16723b5a","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"d017d885-8901-475f-b1f2-9d90efaa5b05","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Financing Policy Choices","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"2ce3d21f-d8c6-4250-99ad-6ca537d6e0fb","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"335ddbb6-6e13-4a97-aa98-ff197de14226","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Following the matching principle should, in the long run, help minimize a firm’s transaction costs.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"cebac8f2-c19b-4455-b5b9-3b8e6e1c773a","stage":{"ref":"8d4dac67-8496-449a-a77e-1b67915797f7","sections":[{"ref":"755d406b-6ebb-4278-81fe-b23f82789616","rows":[{"ref":"4286d950-1f5a-4ad3-90a2-8027b81cbea8","columns":[{"ref":"acad2dfb-db32-478d-8352-5570271c1dee","stageElements":[{"ref":"4973c148-b69d-4116-8627-f9fc0acccbfc","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"08301fda-1e8d-471e-8c39-ec5b32fe30da","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ef986070-935e-4d4f-96a2-060697dff4b0","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Some evidence indicates that most firms appear to follow the matching principle. See W. Beranek, C. Cornwell, and S. Choi, “External Financing, Liquidity, and Capital Expenditures,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Financial Research","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" (Summer 1995): 207–222; and M. H. Stohs and D. C. Mauer, “The Determinants of Corporate Debt Maturity Structure,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Business","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 69 (3) (1996): 279–312.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"3","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"c8a772aa-5876-4e4d-9b3f-cca816bb736d"},{"object":"text","text":" But what if, instead of using the matching principle, a firm financed its permanent working capital needs with short-term debt? When the short-term debt comes due, the firm will have to negotiate a new loan. This new loan will involve additional transaction costs, and it will carry whatever market interest rate exists at the time. As a result, the firm is also exposed to interest rate risk.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"9e8e4135-d279-4cb4-908b-088cbb542c3e","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"034fda0a-f082-4c93-a7aa-bbed781bb3af","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Aggressive Financing Policy","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"3299f247-9ae0-4ce7-b2f1-d0d661638ed7","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d4bdfefe-8299-435e-97c2-e2197addc718","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Financing part or all of the permanent working capital with short-term debt is known as an ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"a8c0d38d-f458-4bc5-a411-2eb1be0b69c0","stage":{"ref":"6331a0a9-9942-4466-a3c9-a2d2855b6653","sections":[{"ref":"4aa9533c-38f8-4288-8521-3074d3cd1515","rows":[{"ref":"aacfea4d-7179-49ae-907f-02dad82f2814","columns":[{"ref":"42605680-f2d6-40af-a8f4-f7e513ddd7ec","stageElements":[{"ref":"1b66f6a9-130d-4124-9f3e-876a28956bf5","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"d0ba6d96-dea4-4cab-a2a7-21a11455a09b","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"e564deae-07ae-47d9-b90a-baa38e033839","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Financing part or all of a firm’s permanent working capital with short-term debt.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"aggressive financing policy","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"64eabf14-7f41-42a0-be38-88575bbbdeaa"},{"object":"text","text":". An ultra-aggressive policy would involve financing even some of the plant, property, and equipment with short-term sources of funds.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"b40b128d-c210-4fc8-9435-827dbffc0854","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7b1285d7-bcb9-482c-bba9-cf9c2889c150","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When the yield curve is upward sloping, the interest rate on short-term debt is lower than the rate on long-term debt. In that case, short-term debt may appear cheaper than long-term debt. However, we know that with perfect capital markets, Modigliani and Miller’s results from ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"d6231c28-987e-4395-a673-6979be4be408","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 16","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"637adc80-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" apply: The benefit of the lower rate from short-term debt is offset by the risk that the firm will have to refinance the debt in the future at a higher rate. This risk is borne by the equity holders, and so the firm’s equity cost of capital will rise to offset any benefit from the lower borrowing rate.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"d70fab05-c700-4ae8-8403-30741ab2f31a","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"834b4054-e925-4ee2-83fb-b93782adbb2c","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Why, then, might a firm choose an aggressive financing policy? Such a policy might be beneficial if the market imperfections mentioned in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"07ccde2c-6600-4296-adfd-371f8f2d174f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 16","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"637adc80-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", such as agency costs and asymmetric information, are important. The value of short-term debt is less sensitive to the firm’s credit quality than long-term debt; therefore, its value will be less affected by management’s actions or information. As a result, short-term debt can have lower agency and lemons costs than long-term debt, and an aggressive financing policy can benefit shareholders. On the other hand, by relying on short-term debt the firm exposes itself to ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"6be23386-d8c4-466a-bab2-47a479ab4873","stage":{"ref":"d1d98d37-81de-4bac-a177-970db377416e","sections":[{"ref":"f3f9b5a2-0359-4181-86d1-f263fd93616b","rows":[{"ref":"c79079d1-5796-49f1-a527-5ac0b2e0a5a4","columns":[{"ref":"1cd26e63-cb00-44d9-83d2-5f0ea92f1c6a","stageElements":[{"ref":"918bdd35-68b9-472f-a966-3b8c9dc99076","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"d2229539-cf39-4b5a-833e-d203971e9030","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ce4e8ece-0d40-4ef8-88b1-ecff413d584a","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The risk of incurring financial distress costs if a firm cannot refinance its debt in a timely manner or at a reasonable rate.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"funding risk","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"ab2927b2-37d4-4f1b-b1e3-2fb3763a8cb7"},{"object":"text","text":", which is the risk of incurring financial distress costs if it cannot refinance its debt in a timely manner or at a reasonable rate. The box on the commercial paper and the financial crisis (page 641) highlights exactly this risk.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"3a659be7-fdbf-4fc0-a9ea-c10f1e473a3e","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"b60517f0-c799-4a1d-a3b4-8f840cd677a4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Conservative Financing Policy","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"4191f8fd-6487-4925-ba58-898dd471a554","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"e004088f-37de-4118-abb3-79197de5502b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Alternatively, a firm could finance its short-term needs with long-term debt, a practice known as a ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"cccc9417-b588-409a-b5fb-ccc39689f95c","stage":{"ref":"aed72da7-5423-4375-b395-3902667ae2fa","sections":[{"ref":"cf29e985-d1be-4502-8183-ada7a232f131","rows":[{"ref":"1f137273-de20-4514-9165-56aa7307ab16","columns":[{"ref":"b537596b-3dd7-414a-ad8d-1a2a52b670c9","stageElements":[{"ref":"ef4c0d9d-30db-4fb7-893c-d9ddf6e8b795","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"3ade993b-ae4b-434d-93f8-289e2e9115c8","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a2de12e0-4c5a-4e5d-9a32-86728d24d8fe","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When a firm finances its short-term needs with long-term debt.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"conservative financing policy","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"3fa38dfb-5f24-465f-a79f-70cfaf802d5e"},{"object":"text","text":". For example, when following such a policy, a firm would use long-term sources of funds to finance its fixed assets, permanent working capital, and some of its seasonal needs. The firm would use short-term debt very sparingly to meet its peak seasonal needs. To implement such a policy effectively, there will necessarily be periods when excess cash is available—those periods when the firm requires little or no investment in temporary working capital. In an imperfect capital market, this cash will earn a below-market interest rate, thereby reducing the firm’s value. It also increases the possibility that managers of the firm will use this excess cash nonproductively—for example, on perquisites for themselves.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"9265f2c8-918b-45d7-9604-5ebc7c01ab0c","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ec7582be-44f7-420b-9ae7-abb49d26efe7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"In ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"12a782e4-b9b0-44ab-b7c6-3373176791ad","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 20.2","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"9d509df0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", we illustrate aggressive and conservative financial policies for Springfield. With an aggressive policy, Springfield relies entirely on short-term financing to fund its inventory buildup, so its borrowing reaches a peak along with its inventory in the third quarter. With a conservative policy, it uses long-term borrowing to ensure that it will have enough cash to pay for its peak inventory. In this case, Springfield’s borrowing does not fluctuate at all, but rather it draws down its cash reserves so that its cash reserves are at a minimum when its inventory is at its peak.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""}},{"ref":"55e6b294-ddd8-4bd5-a002-6432a7e86748","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"styledText","data":{"styledText":"genericLabel","id":"3"},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 20.2","marks":[]}]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9c5c86fd-dd85-4e24-bbfb-a94184a88dc3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Financing Policy Choices for Springfield Snowboards","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":"figure-title"}},{"ref":"b9e0ddff-d2ea-43b9-9072-e3043d6d9cf1","type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"333543ed-6f67-4c5b-a2b0-c01c414b45d2","name":"FG_20_002a.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998397,"lastSyncDate":1665085940},"source":{"small":{"width":868,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced/small/a1cbf5f55bb7fa027d307d14da3621ff.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":1735,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced/medium/a1cbf5f55bb7fa027d307d14da3621ff.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":1735,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced/medium/a1cbf5f55bb7fa027d307d14da3621ff.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":434,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/50b16700-44e0-11ed-9423-b5340f85eced/thumb/a1cbf5f55bb7fa027d307d14da3621ff.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>Panel (a): Aggressive financing policy: All working capital is financed with short-term debt.</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_20_002a.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"277"}}},"alt":"","caption":"<p>Panel (a): Aggressive financing policy: All working capital is financed with short-term debt.</p>","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"","activityLabel":"","activityTitle":""},"height":277},{"ref":"da21b6a0-a5eb-443d-9b5c-6c7a9e55e6c1","type":"stage-element-text","version":"0.45.1","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"styledText","data":{"styledText":"caption-text","id":"3"},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Assuming $25,000 in fixed assets, the figure shows the levels of fixed assets (green), permanent working capital ($2,125, yellow), and seasonal inventory (gray) for Springfield Snowboards. In Panel (a), each quarter shows the mix of long-term financing (purple) and short-term debt (red) used to finance the assets and working capital. In the aggressive policy illustrated in Panel (a), Springfield maintains no excess cash reserves and instead finances its working capital entirely through short-term borrowing. The amount of borrowing must match the amount of working capital.","marks":[]}]}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"styledText","data":{"styledText":"caption-text","id":"3"},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Panel (b) illustrates a conservative policy, in which Springfield maintains enough cash reserves to cover its peak temporary financing needs. Springfield does this with $30,425 in long-term financing, which is enough to finance its fixed assets, permanent working capital, and peak inventory. Its total working capital is constant at $5,425, but the composition of the working capital varies over the year as it draws down its cash reserves (blue) to build inventory and then replenishes the cash reserves when it sells the inventory.","marks":[]}]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":"fig-caption"}},{"ref":"60beb740-74a6-4eea-8964-55944cb2f24e","type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"a2b505bb-a251-4cfe-8c45-ed5bc6b42401","name":"FG_20_002b.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998398,"lastSyncDate":1665085937},"source":{"small":{"width":870,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/small/85030bd199469dae1c9f4bf6a5421f23.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":1740,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/medium/85030bd199469dae1c9f4bf6a5421f23.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":1740,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/medium/85030bd199469dae1c9f4bf6a5421f23.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":435,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/d23dc520-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/thumb/85030bd199469dae1c9f4bf6a5421f23.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","ca